alized Deployment object to the storage layer\n\n### Layer 3: Storage Backend (etcd3 storage)\n\nThe storage interface delegates to the concrete etcd3 implementation in `github.com/sg-evals/kubernetes--v1.32.0/staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/etcd3/store.go:240-305`. The `store.Create()` method:\n1. Prepares the storage key using `s.prepareKey()`\n2. Validates that no resource version was set (line 253)\n3. Encodes the Deployment object to bytes using `runtime.Encode()` (line 260)\n4. Handles TTL if needed by obtaining a lease from the lease manager (line 269)\n5. Transforms the data using the encryption transformer (line 275)\n6. **Executes the actual write at line 283**: `s.client.Kubernetes.OptimisticPut()` - this is the critical call that persists the Deployment to etcd\n7. Decodes the response and returns the created object\n\n### Layer 4: etcd KV Store (etcd-io/etcd)\n\nThe etcd-io/etcd client is used to perform the actual persistent write. In `github.com/sg-evals/etcd-io-etcd/client/v3/kubernetes/client.go:83-106`, the `Client.OptimisticPut()` method:\n1. Creates a transaction context: `txn := k.KV.Txn(ctx).If(...)`\n2. Adds a condition to check if the key doesn't exist (expectedRevision == 0 for create)\n3. Specifies the PUT operation to execute if the condition succeeds: `clientv3.OpPut(key, string(value), clientv3.WithLease(opts.LeaseID))` (line 87)\n4. Calls `txn.Commit()` to execute the transaction (line 94)\n\nThe transaction is committed in `github.com/sg-evals/etcd-io-etcd/client/v3/txn.go:137-150`. The `txn.Commit()` method constructs a `pb.TxnRequest` with the comparisons, success operations, and failure operations, then sends it to the etcd server via `txn.kv.remote.Txn()` (line 145). This gRPC call sends the transaction to the etcd backend, which executes the atomic operation and returns the revision number.\n\nThe Put operation itself is created by `github.com/sg-evals/etcd-io-etcd/client/v3/op.go:270-274`. The `OpPut()` function creates an Op structure with type tPut and the key-value pair, which gets serialized and sent to etcd.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe complete flow is:\n1. **Client** (client-go): POST request with Deployment JSON\n2. **API Server Handler** (kubernetes): Validates with strategy, converts to internal type\n3. **Registry Storage** (apiserver): Encodes to bytes, applies encryption\n4. **etcd Client** (etcd client library): Builds optimistic transaction with PUT operation\n5. **etcd Server** (etcd): Stores the key-value pair in the persistent data store\n\nThis architecture ensures validation at multiple layers, encryption of data in transit and at rest, and atomic operations through etcd's transactional semantics."
